          Tax Guide
        </div>
        <h1>Standard Deduction 2025: Amounts, Rules, and How It Works</h1>
        <p class="qa-meta">Updated April 2026 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Based on IRS Rev. Proc. 2024-40 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Tax year 2025 (filed in 2026)</p>
        <p>The standard deduction reduces your taxable income by a flat amount set by the IRS each year. For tax year 2025, it is $15,000 for single filers and $30,000 for married filing jointly. Most taxpayers take it because it exceeds their itemized deductions.</p>
        <div class="year-nav">
          <a href="/standard-deduction-2025" class="active">2025 Amounts</a>
          <a href="/standard-deduction-2026">2026 Amounts (Projected)</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="quick-answer">
        <div class="qa-label">Quick Answer</div>
        <h2>2025 Standard Deduction by Filing Status</h2>
        <div class="qa-amounts">
          <div class="qa-amount-item">
            <span class="filing">Single</span>
            <span class="amount">$15,000</span>
          </div>
          <div class="qa-amount-item">
            <span class="filing">Married Filing Jointly</span>
            <span class="amount">$30,000</span>
          </div>
          <div class="qa-amount-item">
            <span class="filing">Head of Household</span>
            <span class="amount">$22,500</span>
          </div>
          <div class="qa-amount-item">
            <span class="filing">Married Filing Separately</span>
            <span class="amount">$15,000</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="ad-zone">
        <div class="ad-zone-label">Advertisement</div>
        <ins class="adsbygoogle" style="display:block"
